Seeing these I can't help but wonder if there's value in having a more generic utility `attempt(fn,fin)` mechanism... e.g. 

```
const attempt = require('internal/util').attempt;
attempt(() => doSomething(), (threw) => doCleanup())
```

where `attempt()` == 

```
function attempt (fn, fin) {
  var threw = true;
  try {
    fn();
    threw = false;
  } finally {
    fin(threw);
  }
}
```

Likely not worth the additional complexity and perf cost tho.

